="https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195810/EMMA_ROTH.0.jpg?quality=90&amp;strip=all&amp;crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&amp;w=48 1x, https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195810/EMMA_ROTH.0.jpg?quality=90&amp;strip=all&amp;crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&amp;w=96 2x" src="https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195810/EMMA_ROTH.0.jpg?quality=90&amp;strip=all&amp;crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&amp;w=96"/></div><div class="_1jiz7rn2 _1jiz7rn3"><span class="_1jiz7rn6">Emma Roth</span><span class="duet--article--timestamp g4xafw2 g4xafw0 _19wv7tc5 _1jiz7rna"><time dateTime="2026-07-02T16:29:41+00:00">Jul 2</time></span></div></div><div class="_4ine551 _4ine550"><div class="_4ine554">Cloudflare is cracking down on “multi-purpose” crawlers.</div><div class="_1y5ugvbf _1y5ugvb0"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph _1044qizi _18mzr4b1 _18mzr4b0 _19wv7tc1">Starting September 15th, <a href="https://blog.cloudflare.com/content-independence-day-ai-options/">Cloudflare will block bots</a> that scrape ad-supported websites for search indexing <em>and</em> AI training at the same time. The goal is to encourage AI companies to separate their crawlers for different purposes, giving publishers more control over which ones to allow into their websites.</p></div></div><div class="_1p001ee0"><div class="_1y5ugvbe"><div class="_1y5ugvb9"><a class="_1y5ugvba" href="https://techcrunch.com/2026/07/01/cloudflares-new-policy-pushes-ai-companies-to-pay-for-publishers-content/" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Cloudflare&#x27;s new policy pushes AI companies to pay for publishers&#x27; content | TechCrunch</a><p class="_1y5ugvbb">[<!-- -->TechCrunch<!-- -->]</p></div></div></div></div><div class="dq5wa40"><span class="dq5wa41"></span><span class="_1044qizr"></span><span class="dq5wa42"><div class="_1jiz7rnb dq